      The board&rsquo;s primary governance failure pattern is recognising risk too late. The Deloitte (2025) survey makes the AI variant of that pattern explicit. Two-thirds of boards acknowledge they lack the knowledge to govern AI risk. 31% have not placed AI on the agenda. Only 17% address it at every meeting. None of those positions is sustainable. The risk does not pause while governance catches up: the World Economic Forum (2026) reports that only 1% of more than 1,300 surveyed risk experts anticipate a calm global outlook over either the two- or ten-year horizon. The risk environment that boards must govern through is one the practitioner consensus considers anything but benign.
    </p>
